{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"93c1f9af-0cf6-45d7-a035-be8fa4dfef5b","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01XqbyPdgPhQ6b2buM5u7Hu2","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating .NET 11 console app"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01VnmSzEUqKfeEajUkTBpw5r","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null; dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check installed .NET SDK versions","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check installed .NET SDK versions"}],"interactionId":"0f82fcbb-df1a-4ed8-99ad-b41fb2815a2a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants a .NET 11 console app that serializes a `Person` record to JSON with PascalCase property names using built-in framework features.\n\nIn .NET 9+, `System.Text.Json` added `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` as a built-in naming policy. Since the record has lowercase parameter names (`name`, `age`), C# will generate properties with those exact names. By default, `System.Text.Json` uses the property names as-is, so without any policy the JSON would have `name` and `age`. To get `Name` and `Age`, we need to set `PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase`.\n\n\nWhen you define a positional record with lowercase parameters like `public record Person(string name, int age)`, the generated properties match the parameter casing exactly, so they're also lowercase. By default, `System.Text.Json` serializes using those property names as-is, but applying the `PascalCase` naming policy will convert them to `Name` and `Age` in the JSON output.\n\nSince we're in May 2026, .NET 11 might be available or in preview (following the November release cycle), so I'll try creating a project targeting it and see what SDKs are actually installed.","outputTokens":704,"requestId":"4828:3BF41F:135A1BA:159BF37:6A0279A7"},"id":"f6eaf23e-5688-4a24-a204-8b5405a43cc3","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:52:07.182Z","parentId":"e9f741d1-db5d-4